{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584186"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:41:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:41:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14426"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.12,0.59,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7121"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47046"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"4906"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6061"},{"type":"tags","id":"7873"},{"type":"tags","id":"9013"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17164"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following types of embolism is most likely to occur as a complication of a long bone fracture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pulmonary thromboembolism","Air embolism","Fat embolism","Cholesterol embolism","Amniotic fluid embolism"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely type of embolism to occur after a fracture of a long bone, such as the femur in this case, is \u003Cstrong\u003Efat embolism\u003C/strong\u003E. Fat embolism syndrome is a well-known complication of long bone fractures, particularly those involving the femur or tibia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen a long bone is fractured, fat globules from the bone marrow can enter the bloodstream. These fat globules can then travel to various organs, most commonly the lungs, causing obstruction of pulmonary vessels which can lead to respiratory distress and hypoxia. They can also affect the brain, leading to neurological symptoms, and the skin, causing a characteristic petechial rash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less likely in this scenario:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary thromboembolism\u003C/strong\u003E, while a potential complication of immobilisation following trauma, is not directly related to the bone fracture itself and would typically occur later in the course of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAir embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with invasive procedures or diving accidents, not bone fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterol embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in older patients with atherosclerotic disease, often following vascular procedures or anticoagulation therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmniotic fluid embolism\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare obstetric emergency that occurs during pregnancy or shortly after delivery, and is not related to bone fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fat embolism is a common complication following long bone fractures due to the release of fat globules into the bloodstream.","Fat emboli can cause respiratory distress, neurological symptoms, and petechial rashes."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. Robbins Basic Pathology (10th ed.). 2017. Elsevier - Health Sciences Division","Kwiatt ME, Seamon MJ. Fat embolism syndrome. Int J Crit Illn Inj Sci. 2013 Jan;3(1):64-8. doi: 10.4103/2229-5151.109426. PMID: 23724388; PMCID: PMC3665122.","Siegel, J. A., \u0026 Saukko, P. J. Encyclopedia of forensic sciences. 2012. Academic Press."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47046"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47046"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T21:27:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T21:28:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7121"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud